        Selling your parents' Brisbane home: practical, emotional, and legal considerations for adult children
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Adult children typically take a leading role when an elderly parent's home needs to be sold. The legal authority, the family dynamics, and the emotional weight all matter, and getting them right protects both the result and the relationships.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The conversation usually begins quietly. A parent in their late seventies or early eighties has lived in the same Brisbane home for thirty, forty, sometimes fifty years. The garden is too much. The stairs are harder than they used to be. A grandchild has noticed that Mum is forgetting things. A sibling has raised the question of whether the home should be sold while there is still time to do it well rather than under crisis pressure.</p>

      <p>From this point, the adult children typically take a leading role. The parent remains at the centre of the decision wherever they retain capacity, but the practical work of researching agents, coordinating with solicitors, managing the property preparation, and communicating across the family generally falls to one or more of the children. This article is for the adult child carrying that load. The aim is to walk through the legal, practical, and emotional ground that almost every family covers, and to flag the decisions that matter most.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who has the legal authority to act</h2>

      <p>The first question to settle is who has the legal authority to instruct an agent, sign a contract, and proceed to settlement. This is not always obvious to families, and acting without the right authority can cause real problems.</p>

      <p>If the parent is alive and has decision-making capacity, they remain the legal owner of the property and the only person who can sign listing authorities, contracts, and settlement documents. Adult children can advise, support, attend meetings, and coordinate logistics, but the parent must sign. The agent should be introduced to the parent directly, and the parent's wishes should be the reference point throughout the campaign.</p>

      <p>If the parent has lost decision-making capacity (often due to dementia or a serious medical event), an Enduring Power of Attorney must be in place for an attorney to act on their behalf. The attorney is usually one or more adult children, but it can be anyone the parent has appointed in advance. Without an EPOA, an application to QCAT (the Queensland Civil and Administrative Tribunal) for a financial administrator may be required, which adds time, cost, and complexity. Families that suspect capacity is declining should put an EPOA in place while the parent still clearly has capacity, not after.</p>

      <p>If the parent has passed away, the executor named in the will has authority to manage the estate sale, typically after a grant of probate is obtained from the Supreme Court of Queensland. Deceased estate sales have their own process and timing considerations, and we cover those in detail in a separate guide. The principle is the same: the right legal authority must be confirmed before any agent is engaged or any contract is signed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The conversation that needs to happen first</h2>

      <p>Before any agent is contacted or any property preparation begins, the family needs to align on a small number of foundational questions. These conversations are easier to have early than late.</p>

      <p>What does the parent want to achieve from the sale. Is the priority maximum sale price, a quick settlement, certainty around the new living arrangement, or some combination. A parent moving into residential aged care may need certainty about timing more than they need the absolute top of the market. A parent downsizing to a unit may have flexibility on settlement and prefer to wait for the right buyer. The parent's priorities, where they retain capacity to express them, should drive the strategy.</p>

      <p>Is the priority downsizing, gifting, or holding the proceeds. Some parents want to gift a portion of the proceeds to children or grandchildren. Others want to retain the full amount to fund their next decade. Each has tax and Centrelink implications that need to be checked before the sale. The decision affects how the proceeds are structured at settlement, so it should be made before listing, not after.</p>

      <p>Are siblings aligned on the approach. Disagreements between siblings are one of the most common sources of friction in this kind of sale. The disagreements are rarely about the sale itself; they are usually about underlying family dynamics that the sale has surfaced. Talking openly early prevents the disagreement becoming an obstacle to the sale.</p>

      <p>Is there a will and is it current. If the parent passes between listing and settlement, the executor named in the will manages the estate. An out-of-date will (one that names a deceased executor, or that does not reflect the current family situation) can cause significant delays. This is a good moment to check.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical preparation: decluttering after decades</h2>

      <p>Many parents have lived in the home for thirty to fifty years. The accumulated possessions of that period are substantial: furniture, books, photographs, paperwork, gardening equipment, decades of items in the garage and the shed. Decluttering is one of the largest practical tasks of the sale, and it cannot be rushed.</p>

      <p>Involve the parent in decisions about possessions wherever they have capacity to participate. What looks like clutter to an adult child may be deeply meaningful to the parent: the chair their late spouse used, the cookbook collection, the Christmas decorations, the children's old school work. Going through these items with the parent is part of how the parent transitions emotionally to the next stage of life. Done well, the decluttering process helps the parent let go; done badly, it strips them of agency at a vulnerable moment.</p>

      <p>Allocate time generously. A home of fifty years cannot be cleared in a weekend. Plan for several months if possible, working through one room at a time. Identify items that family members would like to keep, items that can be sold or donated, and items that should be discarded. Professional declutterers can help with the volume, but the meaningful decisions should be made by the family.</p>

      <p>Respect the parent's pace. Pushing a parent through this process too quickly can damage the relationship and rob the move of its dignity. A few weeks of patience are almost always worth more than the small efficiency gains of speeding the process up.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Financial and tax considerations</h2>

      <p>For a parent who has owned the home for many decades, the financial considerations of the sale are often more nuanced than for a typical seller. A few that families should check with appropriate professionals.</p>

      <p>The main residence CGT exemption almost always applies where the home has been the parent's primary residence throughout ownership, but the rules have edge cases (periods of absence, periods where the home was rented out, mixed-use properties) that should be confirmed with a tax adviser. The exemption is valuable; do not assume it applies without checking.</p>

      <p>Aged care fee implications can be substantial. If the parent is moving into residential aged care, the Refundable Accommodation Deposit (RAD) and ongoing daily fees are means-tested. The proceeds of the home sale affect the calculation, sometimes significantly. Specialist aged care financial advice (from an adviser accredited in this area) is essential before the sale settles. The advice can change how the proceeds are structured, where they are held, and whether part of the home value is retained or released.</p>

      <p>Centrelink implications matter for parents receiving the Age Pension or other benefits. The proceeds of a home sale are treated differently from the home itself for assets-test purposes, and the timing of receipts can affect pension entitlements. Again, this is a specialist area; general financial advice is rarely sufficient.</p>

      <p>The financial timing question. Selling before the parent's situation forces an urgent sale gives time to maximise the result. A campaign run under crisis pressure (the parent has had a fall, an aged care bed is available next month, the family needs to act immediately) almost always achieves a worse outcome than a campaign with three to four months of runway. If the sale is foreseeable, plan early.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The family relationship dynamics</h2>

      <p>Siblings often have different views on the sale: different views on price, on timing, on the agent, on what is fair. These differences are normal, but they need a process to resolve, or they become the bottleneck of the campaign.</p>

      <p>Agree on a decision-making process before listing. The most workable structure in practice is a single decision-maker (one sibling, with consultation across the family), rather than committee decisions. Committee decisions slow the campaign down at every step (every agent meeting needs three siblings on the call; every offer needs a family discussion before it can be responded to) and tend to surface disagreements at exactly the moments where speed matters. A single decision-maker, who consults the family but holds the authority to instruct the agent, almost always works better.</p>

      <p>Tell the agent who has authority to make decisions. The agent needs to know who they should be calling at 6pm on a Saturday when an offer comes in. Clarity on this point removes a lot of friction.</p>

      <p>Acknowledge that money surfaces old family dynamics. Disagreements about the sale price, or about who should pay for what during the campaign, often have roots that go back decades. The sale is rarely the cause; it is usually the trigger. Recognising this can help families avoid escalating sale-related disagreements into broader family conflicts.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The emotional weight of the sale</h2>

      <p>For many families, selling the family home is one of the most emotionally significant property transactions they will ever experience. The home is where children were raised, where holidays were spent, where a partner may have passed away. The decision to sell, even when it is the right decision, carries grief.</p>

      <p>Give parents time to grieve the move even if they want to downsize. A parent can simultaneously want to leave and feel sad about leaving. Both are real, and rushing past the sadness rarely serves anyone.</p>

      <p>Consider whether the parent should attend open homes. Some parents find open homes deeply distressing: strangers walking through their kitchen, opening cupboards, commenting on rooms. Other parents find it interesting and want to be involved. The right answer depends on the parent. Ask them directly, and follow their lead.</p>

      <p>Photograph the home before it is decluttered if there is sentimental value in doing so. The home as it is, full of the parent's life, will not exist again after the move. A simple set of photographs (not the agent's marketing photos, but personal ones) preserves something that the family will value later.</p>

      <p>Be patient through settlement. The day of the move is emotional even when everything goes smoothly. Plan for a quiet day rather than a packed one. The parent will appreciate the calm.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical role of the adult child</h2>

      <p>For the adult child carrying most of the practical work, a short list of what tends to be involved.</p>

      <p>Research and shortlist agents. Two or three agents who know the suburb well, who can demonstrate recent comparable sales, and who can communicate clearly with the parent. The agent should be introduced to the parent before being engaged, and the parent should feel comfortable with the choice.</p>

      <p>Coordinate with the parent's solicitor. The solicitor handles contract review, settlement, and any estate-related matters. If the parent does not currently have a solicitor, engaging one early (ideally before any contract is signed) is the right step.</p>

      <p>Manage the property preparation. Decluttering, gardener, cleaner, any repairs the agent recommends. The work is almost always more than expected. Plan generously.</p>

      <p>Attend agent meetings and open homes if appropriate. The agent benefits from a consistent point of contact in the family. Showing up communicates that the campaign matters to the family.</p>

      <p>Communicate with siblings. Regular updates, even brief ones, prevent siblings feeling excluded and reduce the likelihood of late-stage disagreement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to avoid</h2>

      <p>Do not push the parent into a sale they are not ready for. The financial gain of a faster sale rarely outweighs the relationship cost of a parent who feels rushed or overruled. Where the parent retains capacity, their pace is the right pace.</p>

      <p>Do not let one sibling dominate decisions when other siblings are equal beneficiaries. Even if one sibling is doing most of the practical work, the financial decisions affect everyone equally and should be made with full transparency.</p>

      <p>Do not undertake significant renovations to "modernise" the home. Presentation matters, but cosmetic upgrades on a home that is likely to sell to a renovator buyer are usually wasted. A clean, well-presented home generally outperforms a half-renovated one. The agent will advise on what is worth doing and what is not.</p>

      <p>Do not assume the parent's wishes from a previous conversation still hold. A parent's view of the sale can shift as the move approaches. Check in regularly. Ask, do not assume.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>

      <p>Respect the parent's authority where they retain capacity. They are still the legal owner and, more importantly, the central figure in the decision. The role of the family is to support, not to override.</p>

      <p>Use professional advice. A solicitor for the legal work, a tax adviser for the CGT and main residence questions, a specialist aged care financial adviser if aged care is involved, and a good agent for the sale itself. Each is an investment that protects the result.</p>

      <p>Communicate openly with siblings and with the parent. Most family friction in this kind of sale comes from poor communication rather than genuine disagreement. Regular, simple updates prevent most of it.</p>

      <p>Be patient with the emotional process. The family relationships outlast any single sale. Protect them.</p>

